-- LLM evaluation:
-- The prompt now asks for design rationale (why over alternatives), explicit
-- error model for sagas, and composition semantics. The LLM produces a
-- comprehensive architectural briefing:

  yield summary ≡ "ARCHITECTURAL BRIEFING — Event-Driven Module

This module layers three patterns from general to specific. Each solves a distinct decoupling problem.

1. EventBus — PUBLISH/SUBSCRIBE + MIDDLEWARE PIPELINE
   PATTERNS: (a) Pub/sub decouples event producers from consumers. (b) The middleware pipeline (chain of responsibility) decouples cross-cutting concerns from handler logic.
   WHY PUB/SUB: Producers don't need to know which handlers exist or in what order they run. Adding a handler requires zero changes to emit-side code. Priority ordering (not just FIFO) lets critical handlers (e.g. security validation) run before others.
   WHY MIDDLEWARE: Middleware separates cross-cutting concerns (logging, auth, rate-limiting) from business handlers. Unlike decorators, middleware is registered centrally and applies to ALL events — no per-handler wrapping. Middleware can cancel events entirely (ctx['cancelled']=True), acting as a gate.
   EXTENSION: on(event, handler, priority) to add handlers. use(middleware_fn) to add middleware. Both are additive — no existing code changes.

2. TypedBus — SCHEMA VALIDATION LAYER (extends EventBus)
   PATTERN: Contract enforcement via schema registry — the decorator pattern applied to the bus.
   WHY: Fail-fast at the emit boundary. Without validation, a malformed payload silently reaches handlers, causing cryptic downstream errors. TypedBus catches structural errors before middleware or handlers execute.
   COMPOSITION: TypedBus IS-A EventBus (inheritance). It overrides emit() to validate, then delegates to super().emit(). All middleware and handlers work unchanged — the validation is transparent.
   EXTENSION: Register schemas per event type in schema_registry.

3. create_saga — SAGA/COMPENSATION PATTERN
   PATTERN: Saga with compensating transactions — the choreography alternative to distributed transactions.
   WHY: Multi-step workflows need all-or-nothing semantics. Traditional transactions don't work across async event-driven systems. The saga pattern provides rollback via explicit compensation functions.
   ERROR MODEL: If step N raises an exception, steps N-1 through 0 are compensated in REVERSE ORDER by calling each compensate_fn(). IMPORTANT LIMITATION: compensation only undoes step side-effects. If steps emitted bus events, those events are NOT recalled — handlers that already processed them will have stale state. This is an inherent limitation of sagas without event sourcing.
   COMPOSITION: create_saga takes a bus parameter — it can use EventBus (unvalidated) or TypedBus (validated). Validated sagas catch payload errors BEFORE executing steps, preventing partial-execution scenarios from schema violations.
   EXTENSION: Add steps as (step_fn, compensate_fn) tuples. Order matters — steps execute sequentially, compensations reverse.

END-TO-END DATA FLOW:
  caller → bus.emit(event, payload)
    → middleware chain: each mw(ctx) transforms or cancels
    → [TypedBus only] schema_registry.validate(payload)
    → priority-sorted handlers: each handler(payload) → results[]
    → return results (or None if cancelled by middleware)"

